Yes — in Spring Boot you can configure your DataSource without using application.properties.
There are several alternative ways, depending on what you want.

Below are the main options:

⸻

✅ 1. Use application.yml instead of application.properties

A simple alternative file format:

spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb
    username: root
    password: root
    driver-class-name: com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver


⸻

✅ 2. Use Java configuration (@Configuration + @Bean)

You can fully define the DataSource in Java code, without any properties file.

@Configuration
public class DataSourceConfig {

    @Bean
    public DataSource dataSource() {
        DriverManagerDataSource dataSource = new DriverManagerDataSource();
        dataSource.setDriverClassName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");
        dataSource.setUrl("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb");
        dataSource.setUsername("root");
        dataSource.setPassword("root");
        return dataSource;
    }
}

➡️ In this case, remove all spring.datasource.* from application.properties.

⸻

✅ 3. Use environment variables (no properties file needed)

Spring Boot automatically maps environment variables to properties.

Example environment variables:

SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb
SPRING_DATASOURCE_USERNAME=root
SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD=root
SPRING_DATASOURCE_DRIVER-CLASS-NAME=com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver

This works in Docker, Kubernetes, or IntelliJ “Run/Debug Configurations”.

⸻

✅ 4. Use command-line arguments

You can launch your app like this:

java -jar app.jar \
  --spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb \
  --spring.datasource.username=root \
  --spring.datasource.password=root


⸻

✅ 5. Use a custom @PropertySource

You can create your own config file:

datasource.properties:

my.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb
my.user=root
my.pass=root

Then load it:

@Configuration
@PropertySource("classpath:datasource.properties")
public class DataSourceConfig {

    @Value("${my.url}")
    private String url;

    @Value("${my.user}")
    private String user;

    @Value("${my.pass}")
    private String pass;

    @Bean
    public DataSource dataSource() {
        DriverManagerDataSource ds = new DriverManagerDataSource();
        ds.setUrl(url);
        ds.setUsername(user);
        ds.setPassword(pass);
        ds.setDriverClassName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");
        return ds;
    }
}


⸻

❗ Important: You must still include the database driver dependency

Example for MySQL (in pom.xml):

<dependency>
    <groupId>mysql</groupId>
    <artifactId>mysql-connector-j</artifactId>
</dependency>

Without this, Spring Boot cannot detect a driver and you get:

Failed to determine a suitable driver class

⸻

